Unsupervised Learning Project: AllLife Bank Customer Segmentation¶

Marks: 30¶

Welcome to the project on Unsupervised Learning. We will be using Credit Card Customer Data for this project.

Context¶

AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this input, the marketing team proposes to run personalized campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers.

Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the bank poorly. Based on this, the operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customers' queries are resolved faster. The head of marketing and the head of delivery, both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help.

Objective¶

Identify different segments in the existing customer base, taking into account their spending patterns as well as past interactions with the bank.

About the data¶

Data is available on customers of the bank with their credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which the customer has contacted the bank for any queries. These different channels include visiting the bank, online, and through a call center.

  • Sl_no - Customer Serial Number
  • Customer Key - Customer identification
  • Avg_Credit_Limit - Average credit limit (currency is not specified, you can make an assumption around this)
  • Total_Credit_Cards - Total number of credit cards
  • Total_visits_bank - Total bank visits
  • Total_visits_online - Total online visits
  • Total_calls_made - Total calls made

Data Preprocessing and Exploratory Data Analysis¶

  • EDA is an important part of any project involving data.
  • It is important to investigate and understand the data better before building a model with it.
  • A few questions have been mentioned below which will help you approach the analysis in the right manner and generate insights from the data.
  • A thorough analysis of the data, in addition to the questions mentioned below, should be done.
  • Check and drop the duplicate customer keys
  • Drop the variables that are not required for the analysis
  • Check duplicate rows and remove them.

Questions:

  1. How does the distribution and outliers look for each variable in the data?
  2. How are the variables correlated with each other?

data.describe().T

#We made the choice to drop duplicate rows completely, but we'll also carry along a copy of the data that instead
#opts to use average values.
av_data=data.groupby('Customer Key').mean().reset_index()

Observations:

  • The Serial Number statistics show that it is a simple enumeration from 1 to 655 and doesn't add information to the data.
  • While having no null values, Customer Key had 5 repeat values. We've elected to drop the repeats.
  • Credit Limit goes from 3k to 200k, with a mean of 34k 37k even though the median is only 18k, which suggests a strong right skew. Also, the wide of the data corroborates this, given that the mean - is less than 0.
  • Customers have between 1 and 10 credit cards, most between 3 and 7.
  • Customers make between 0 and 5 bank visits, most between 2 and 4
  • Customers make between 0 and 15 online visits, most between 0 and 6, showing a right skew to the data.
  • Customers make between 0 and 10 calls, most between 1 and 6, again with a right skew in the data.

In summary There seem to be a handful of heavy users with any type of contact. Like most financial data, which is innately a product of some type of exponential growth process, credit limit is right skewed.

Observations

  • Customer Key has predicably low correlations with an other variables.
  • We have modest correlations between credit limit, total number of credit cards, and online visits.
  • Online visits is negatively correlated with in-person visits, which makes sense. As a result, people with more credit cards and higher credit limit use online more but call less.
  • Serial number is surprisingly correlated with number of credit cars, credit limit, and bank visits, while being inverse correlated to total calls made. This would suggest that there is ordering to the customer serial number, most likely a time ordering. Later customers might be assigned later serial numbers and these customers are heavier card users with more bank visits. Some of this might also be a larger number of similar customers coming in in a batch (e.g. all from one referral, one business, etc..). Let's investigate....

It is uneqiuivocally clear that we are getting batches of similiar customers being assigned adjacent Customer Serial Numbers. Again, this might be time-ordering or the system might be assigning a Serial Number based on another attribute such as branch location.

These blocks are likely overwhelming all other patterns in the data to produce the correlations we see. Earlier Sl_No's had fewer credit cards, smaller credit limit, fewer total visits, and more calls compared to later Sl_No's.

K-Means¶

Let us now fit the K-means algorithm on our pca components and find out the optimum number of clusters to use.

We will do this in 3 steps:

  1. Initialize a dictionary to store the Sum of Squared Error (SSE) for each K
  2. Run for a range of Ks and store SSE for each run
  3. Plot the SSE vs K and plot the elbow curve
In [102]:
# Empty dictionary to store the SSE for each value of K
sse = {}

# Iterate for a range of Ks and fit the scaled data to the algorithm.
# Use inertia attribute from the clustering object and store the inertia value for that K
for k in range(1, 10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = k, random_state = 1).fit(data_scaled)

    sse[k] = kmeans.inertia_

# Elbow plot
plt.figure()

plt.plot(list(sse.keys()), list(sse.values()), 'bx-')

plt.xlabel("Number of cluster")

plt.ylabel("SSE")

plt.show()
  • The sudden drop in slope at k=3 seems a good place to choose. We've also observed in the raw scatterplots above data highly suggestive for 3 groups.
  • Fit the K-means algorithms on the pca components with the number of clusters for the chosen value of K, but it can't hurt to look at the Sil score:
In [103]:
# Empty dictionary to store the Silhouette score for each value of K
sc = {}

# Iterate for a range of Ks and fit the scaled data to the algorithm. Store the Silhouette score for that K
for k in range(2, 10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = k, random_state = 1).fit(data_scaled)

    labels = kmeans.predict(data_scaled)

    sc[k] = silhouette_score(data_scaled, labels)

# Elbow plot
plt.figure()

plt.plot(list(sc.keys()), list(sc.values()), 'bx-')

plt.xlabel("Number of cluster")

plt.ylabel("Silhouette Score")

plt.show()

This further reinforces our decision to use k=3, as k=3 gives a clear maximum in putting like points in the same cluster and dissimilar points into differnt clusters.

Compare the clusters from K-Means and K-Medoids¶

This confirms what we've seen above - that while Cluster 2 can be reasonably segregated if only considering PC1, it has now been inappropropriately split across PC2. Additionally, roughly half of the bottom cluster, which should be with cluster0, has been taken by cluster 2.

Let's check out the silhouette score and compared to 0.53, obtained with KMeans.

In [136]:
kmedoLabels = kmedo.predict(data_scaled)

0.22955053307399242

Silhouette score confirms what already seems obvious from visual inspection. N.b. I have attempted to initialize Kmedoids with different random states and the results in this latest plot seem robust to different initializations.

Conclusions and Recommendations¶

Based on this input, the marketing team proposes to run personalized campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers.

...customers perceive the support services of the bank poorly. Based on this, the operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customers' queries are resolved faster.

  • My first recommendation would be to understand the nature of the Customer Serial Number, as it already seems to embed a great deal of clustering information that data engineers may be able to shed light on.

  • Regarding the targeting of new customers,

    • I would venture to guess that Group 0, with their larger amount of phone contact would be an older segment of the population or who otherwise does not have easy broadband access (worth cross-referencing with any available demographic data). This group should be targeted accordingly and the bank's positive performance with phone support should be emphasized (e.g. "Typical hold times less than 5 minutes. You'll get a person on the other end of the line, who cares about you.")
    • Group 1 comes into the bank physically a lot more so these may be those who simply live or work close to a physical branch. These potential customers can likely be reached with physical ads such as billboards, bus and subway signs.
    • Group 2 is the likely high-powered young professionals, who consistently use online services for their heavy credit card use and high number of cards. This group can be reached via online ads in Instagram or even Tik Tok.

    Perhaps most usefully, customer dissatisfaction data should be collected to determine which group needs to be most catered to and focus efforts on that medium specifically to maximize cost effectivness of the intervention. E.g. if the only customers who are dissatisfied fit clearly into Group 1, hire more tellers; if dissatisfied customers are from Group 2, invest in redesigning or otherwise improving the website; if from Group 0, hire more phone operators.
